Data Modelling – Partitioning ⭐⭐⭐

(One of the Most Important Performance Topics in Data Engineering)

First — What Problem Does Partitioning Solve?

Imagine a huge fact table at Amazon:

fact_sales

date	customer	revenue

Suppose:
10 billion rows
5 years of data

Now query:
SELECT *
FROM fact_sales
WHERE sale_date = '2026-01-01';

Without partitioning:

database scans huge table

query becomes slow

massive I/O cost


Partitioning solves this.

---

What is Partitioning?

Theory

Partitioning divides a large table into smaller physical segments based on a column.

Each segment is called:

partition


---

Simple Definition
Instead of one huge table:
split data into manageable chunks
---

Example — Date Partitioning ⭐
fact_sales
Partitioned by month:
fact_sales_2026_jan
fact_sales_2026_feb
fact_sales_2026_mar

Now query for January only scans January partition.

Huge performance improvement.


---

Important Insight ⭐

Partitioning:
changes physical storage
not logical business meaning
Users still query same table.
---
Most Common Partition Column
Date / Time ⭐⭐⭐
Because:
data naturally grows over time
most queries filter by date
Extremely common in:
warehouses
Spark
BigQuery
Snowflake
---
How Query Performance Improves

Without partitioning:
Scan 10 billion rows
With partitioning:
Scan only January partition
This is called:
Partition Pruning ⭐

Very important interview term.
---

What is Partition Pruning?

Database reads only relevant partitions instead of entire table.
---
Example
WHERE sale_date = '2026-01-01'
Only January partition scanned.
---

Types of Partitioning
1. Range Partitioning ⭐
Data split by ranges.
Example:
monthly
yearly
salary ranges
Most common warehouse type.
---

Example
2025 partition
2026 partition
2027 partition


---

2. List Partitioning
Based on fixed categories.
Example:
India partition
US partition
UK partition
---
3. Hash Partitioning
Rows distributed using hash function.
Used for:
balancing data
parallelism
---
4. Composite Partitioning
Combination of multiple methods.
Example:
range + hash
Advanced systems.
---

Real Warehouse Example
At Netflix
Watch events table may partition by:
watch_date
Because most analytics are time-based.
---

Why Partitioning Is Important ⭐⭐⭐

1. Faster Queries
Most important advantage.
---
2. Reduced I/O
Less disk scanning.
---

3. Better Parallel Processing

Multiple partitions processed simultaneously.
---

4. Easier Data Management

Can archive/drop old partitions.
---

Example — Archiving

Drop old 2020 partition directly.
Instead of deleting billions of rows.
Huge operational benefit.
---

Partitioning vs Indexing ⭐
Very common interview question.

Partitioning	Indexing
Splits table physically	Creates lookup structure
Reduces scan size	Speeds row search
Good for huge scans	Good for point lookups

Both solve different problems.
---
Important Interview Insight ⭐
Partitioning works best when queries frequently filter on partition column.

Very important statement.


---



Common Interview Questions

Q1. What is partitioning?

Splitting large tables into smaller physical segments.


---

Q2. Why partition tables?

Improve query performance and scalability.


---

Q3. Most common partition column?

Date/time.


---

Q4. What is partition pruning?

Scanning only required partitions.


---

Q5. Difference between partitioning and indexing?

Partitioning reduces scanned data volume; indexing improves lookup access.


